At a time when we are enjoying longer, more healthful lives, ominous headlines, announces: 'Researchers tie Aluminum to Alzheimer's Disease ' and 'Coffee linked to Cholestrol Rise'. As a result of alarming and something ambiguous bulletins, worriers often become major threats and speculations about disease prevention become 'proven' cures. Part to the problem isthat the media often trumpet the questionable research finding as major medical breakthroughs. In 1985, three French scientists told reporters at a press that the drug Cyclosporine appeared to halt the grownth of AIDS Virus. They based the announcement on their observation of Two AIDS patients treated for 8 days. Never mind no actual study had been done; for the media the announcement was enough, and the story became frontpage news around the world. Unfortunately one of the patient died within days. Cyclosporine was no miracle cure.
